{"annotations":[{"start_time":2,"end_time":22,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Students in the audience nod and mumble along. Responding when Adler asks if they know what \"The Norm is\""}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"The Norm","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"9bb8c552-d168-46bf-b000-d965f61058f7"},{"start_time":44,"end_time":44,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses the idea that the greatest gift give to an actor is \"being himself.\""}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"The Truth","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"ae88d683-f7f0-4b95-b069-5369fb022c37"},{"start_time":48,"end_time":53,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler’s hands gesticulate in rhythm with her speech"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Laurence Olivier","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"acb6fb0b-f210-4a94-af13-134710efea83"},{"start_time":90,"end_time":90,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"One hand in a fist while talking"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Closed Fist","category":"Body Language and Gestures"}],"uuid":"ed213f9f-2c2b-41aa-9f6f-2426c7fcb153"},{"start_time":101,"end_time":101,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler asks who is shy and implores students to \"come on up\" to the stage with a come hither motion"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"e9cb3d63-6493-4071-aa0c-d5e32b059f80"},{"start_time":115,"end_time":115,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"All of the \"shy\" students to come up on stage are women"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Gender"}],"uuid":"68396dc5-8909-41fa-ad3c-d5ab3a230481"},{"start_time":120,"end_time":150,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"A discussion of shyness in general followed by imploring students to look at her and then at the audience"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"dee4105c-f433-4620-8346-35998e2c099a"},{"start_time":155,"end_time":155,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Shaking students hands"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Student Interaction","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"8d9b4c0f-08ef-4632-bd98-722689b62a55"},{"start_time":163,"end_time":163,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"\"I shook Miss Adler’s hand.\" Adler asks student to tell the audience what she’s done. Student seems nervous."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"fd8767cd-74f6-4b19-b38a-3451ac334130"},{"start_time":165,"end_time":205,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses talking in and shyness in general and young people and shyness"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Voice","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"c2238620-5fd7-4f37-bbf8-377d9ace8125"},{"start_time":208,"end_time":213,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Speaking in unison they repeat after Adler"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"f20cf419-7015-48ab-87e2-21e1a5f656e7"},{"start_time":214,"end_time":214,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"\"I live now with the birds in Hollywood.\""}]}],"tags":[{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Joke"},{"tag":"Film Industry","category":"Film and Media"}],"uuid":"8aa8baf6-1151-499f-9494-b8304774acb7"},{"start_time":228,"end_time":228,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Wagging finger"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Gesticulating","category":"Body Language and Gestures"}],"uuid":"3ec370c0-d9b5-4745-b9a1-b6e6692a6521"},{"start_time":230,"end_time":282,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Talking in and talking out. Withdrawing is against human nature. It’s going to murder you!"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Hyperbole","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"},{"tag":"Human Nature","category":"Theory and Analysis"}],"uuid":"059ed847-c7a5-495f-bfc7-629a198367e8"},{"start_time":284,"end_time":284,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"There’s a major cut in the recording and it seems like another lesson"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Recording","category":"Film and Media"}],"uuid":"cd7ef016-b801-457f-ab62-5eca8deaa408"},{"start_time":288,"end_time":302,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses the situation for the student actors. It is a scene from the play The Father by Strindberg."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"August Strindberg","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"b14949b7-b23e-40ee-9104-a3c49b96c5d8"},{"start_time":303,"end_time":360,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"The man and the woman are in conflict over the child’s education. The man wants to maintain authority to avoid emasculation."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Gender"},{"tag":"Masculinity","category":"Cultural and National Context"}],"uuid":"2b21ad4c-1ff5-47da-95bb-12461328aa36"},{"start_time":367,"end_time":367,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Distinguishing between the woman in Ibsen and the woman in Strindberg."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"August Strindberg","category":"Theater and Drama"},{"tag":"Anton Chekov","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"39925699-da06-40ed-a862-a18d1e9623d9"},{"start_time":389,"end_time":389,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Emphasizes power struggle with balled fists and introduces the two student actors"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"}],"uuid":"c2e21aef-21b8-46ac-93ab-c7a656d42b11"},{"start_time":395,"end_time":656,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Students act out scene from The Father involving the family in debt and the mother’s expenses being tracked. The father interfering in her idea of how the child should be raised. Men as purchasing women and therefore the mother has no right over her child. Wife uses the logic that since we cannot know for sure who the father of a child is the mother should be in charge of raising the child. Husband dismisses the possibility that his wife may have \"been unfaithful.\""}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Class","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Economics"},{"tag":"Family","category":"Audience and Environment"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Gender"},{"tag":"August Strindberg","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"a52e0da2-4095-4c67-be68-adac31f5e21c"},{"start_time":656,"end_time":664,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Clapping"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Environment","category":"Audience and Environment"}],"uuid":"eb85f78e-a102-4a0e-b3f7-56efb442fe4a"},{"start_time":667,"end_time":667,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Begin new section of recording. Voiceover recording. Two men act out a scene from the play Time Limit by Karl Malden."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Recording","category":"Film and Media"},{"tag":"Karl Malden","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"487cdce9-a99c-4891-814b-08a28b8fc86b"},{"start_time":680,"end_time":899,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Scene from Time Limit"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Students","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Military","category":"Theory and Analysis"},{"tag":"Cold War","category":"Theory and Analysis"},{"tag":"Communism","category":"Theory and Analysis"},{"tag":"Human Nature","category":"Theory and Analysis"}],"uuid":"e1f0bf22-5003-4810-9071-ad1b47941e21"},{"start_time":901,"end_time":910,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Clapping"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Environment","category":"Audience and Environment"}],"uuid":"4930a601-780b-4d8a-925e-278e4601dc30"},{"start_time":911,"end_time":937,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler begins critique of the scene, especially involving characterization."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"The Method","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"},{"tag":"The Truth","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"79c0a2bd-6629-4c0c-a95d-7ed3cc525371"},{"start_time":938,"end_time":1000,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses playing evil characters and that one must decide what the character is going to be. That he is necessarily different from the actor himself. The actor is NOT a \"sniveling\" major and doesn't think like one. So he must make the character different from himself."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"The Method","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Imagination"}],"uuid":"f2444701-4a75-49e8-8416-8454c7725040"},{"start_time":1001,"end_time":1025,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler characterizes her sense of The Major. That he uses his mind and does not easily lose his temper. She becomes increasingly loud and impassioned."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Characterization","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"5c8e1fb8-df39-42c4-9a39-bf3b3707d4b9"},{"start_time":1025,"end_time":1025,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler emphatically points upwards with one finger while taking on the characterization of The Major."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Characterization","category":"Acting and Performance Techniques"}],"uuid":"4a43acdb-3ea1-4210-b036-112fc44bb6c7"},{"start_time":1027,"end_time":1079,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler interprets the situation as being about democracy vs. the idea of a dog eat dog world. She asks the student if he is a strong and articulate man. He says yes. She says a strong and articulate man is \"pulled together.\""}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Democracy","category":"Cultural and National Context"},{"tag":"Masculinity","category":"Cultural and National Context"}],"uuid":"2c3b5ca8-10e6-487a-80f7-2871a680df12"},{"start_time":1080,"end_time":1110,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses how the actor must create a comportment and how he must \"build\" the body of a character. A strong man does not slouch. She begins to discuss social realism."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Realism","category":"Theory and Analysis"}],"uuid":"b522b477-830e-4d37-95c6-7e520c6f5b43"},{"start_time":1110,"end_time":1130,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler critiques casualness and discusses the level of detail necessary to \"help the play\" maintain its sense of realism."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Teaching","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Costume","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"78f98309-811d-441f-b7dc-f69e0883920e"},{"start_time":1131,"end_time":1131,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Break in recording begin new clip of a television interview with Adler"}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Recording","category":"Film and Media"}],"uuid":"d4eb2983-eadb-4696-ab00-c91a7bf8a52c"},{"start_time":1133,"end_time":1148,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"The interviewer asks whether locale makes a difference for the actor and implies that Adler has just recently moved \"here\" aka Los Angeles."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"Interviewer","category":"Film and Media"}],"uuid":"c83fd949-4d6f-4a8e-a42b-b510dade70df"},{"start_time":1149,"end_time":1189,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler discusses the role that place has upon the actor. But that actors are the same everywhere. They are \"fanatics.\" And in the US that means studying to become an actor."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"The Acting Life","category":"Theater and Drama"}],"uuid":"b9c72fe6-9a1e-40de-b04e-69774136e3d8"},{"start_time":1190,"end_time":1236,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler states that the actor is dedicated to himself, then the personality that sells, then he is dedicated to money, then to his family, then to his swimming pool (joke), then more dedicated to his property"}]}],"tags":[{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Technique"},{"tag":"Class","category":"Teaching and Classroom Interaction"},{"tag":"Capitalism","category":"Theory and Analysis"},{"tag":"Family","category":"Audience and Environment"}],"uuid":"27c9d7ac-d085-4ee6-bc06-0ec69f4514ed"},{"start_time":1237,"end_time":1282,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Adler says that in America the theater has been a victim of success, mechanization. But now it is coming of age. We need a National theater of American ideas that states those ideas in Europe. American actors excel at making the world laugh, but we must also make it think."}]}],"tags":[{"tag":"America","category":"Cultural and National Context"},{"tag":"National Identity","category":"Cultural and National Context"}],"uuid":"1a10db3d-d7c7-4da9-bc57-378715b24c52"},{"start_time":1283,"end_time":1308,"annotation":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"The actor must not simply say, make me famous. But what can I say to the world. Adler discusses different acting schools associated with national identities."}]}],"tags":[{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"National identity"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Moscow arts"},{"tag":"Comedy Francais","category":"Theater and Drama"},{"category":"_uncategorized_","tag":"Swedish theater"}],"uuid":"c7d710e3-2b05-4b9e-9c8c-72e770deaf09"}],"set":"Default","event_id":"81be2970-1e75-4d65-a302-70e0732f3f9d","source_id":"32773108-795d-4f91-9146-7fbf75cee408"}